          <div style="margin-left: 0px; position: relative; width: 1000px; z-index: 5; " id="body_layer">
            <div style="height: 0px; line-height: 0px; " class="bumper"> </div>
            <div id="id3" style="height: 269px; left: 403px; position: absolute; top: 60px; width: 583px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_2 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content style_External_583_269" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="style_2">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">One of the most used formula’s in finance is Taylor Series expansions. I think Leibniz rule is one of the most important mathematical rule used in Quantitative finance. I am referring to integral under differential sign. <br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">Consider the complex double integral shown in the picture. f(y) might be a complicated function to solve and a beginner might solve first the inner integral to get tan-1(x) which effectively becomes tan-1(y) and then solve the integral f(y) * tan-1(y) and again differentiate it. If f(y) is tough to solve it becomes a nightmare, but a shortcut is that I can write the solution in one step without bothering about f(y). </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div id="id4" style="height: 20px; left: 402px; position: absolute; top: 28px; width: 583px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_3 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content style_External_583_20" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="style_3">
                  <p style="padding-bottom: 0pt; padding-top: 0pt; " class="Summary_Title">Shortcuts</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            


            <div style="height: 281px; width: 375px;  height: 281px; left: 15px; position: absolute; top: 22px; width: 375px; z-index: 1; " class="tinyText style_SkipStroke_4">
              <img src="tylbz_files/droppedImage.jpg" alt="" style="border: none; height: 282px; width: 375px; " />
            </div>
            


            <div id="id5" style="height: 255px; left: 17px; position: absolute; top: 346px; width: 969px; z-index: 1; " class="style_SkipStroke_1 shape-with-text">
              <div class="text-content graphic_textbox_layout_style_default_External_969_255" style="padding: 0px; ">
                <div class="graphic_textbox_layout_style_default">
                  <p style="padding-top: 0pt; " class="paragraph_style">Leibniz integral under differentiation sign when applied simplifies the function. Generally people apply this rule to single integrals, but trick is to consider in this case the inner integral as just a function so y will get replaced with p and since partial derivative of f(y) with p is 0, it’s simply<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">f(p) * partial derivative of p / dp = f(p) and the inner integral becomes tan-1(x) with y replaced by p, and well a one liner solution f(p) * tan-1(p).<br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style"><br /></p>
                  <p class="paragraph_style">You can verify this result by assuming f(y) = some simple function of y<br /></p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
